Step 1 — Title banner

Add a merged title row across all columns at the top saying "HR Experience Project Tracker" with a dark navy background and white bold Arial text.

Step 2 — Workstream header rows

For every row where the Action Item column is blank, apply a light blue background (#D6E4F0) with dark navy bold text and merge it across all columns.

Step 3 — Alternating row colours

Apply alternating white and light grey (#F7F9FC) fill to all data rows except the header and workstream rows.

Step 4 — Status colours

Apply conditional formatting to the Status column so that: "Done" = green fill with dark green text, "In Progress" = amber fill with dark amber text, "To Do" = grey fill with grey text, "Blocked" = red fill with dark red text.

Step 5 — Priority colours

Apply conditional formatting to the Priority column so that "High" = bold red text, "Medium" = bold amber text, "Low" = bold green text.

Step 6 — Gantt bars

In the weekly date columns, highlight each cell blue if the date in that column's header falls between the Start and End date in the same row.

Step 7 — Freeze panes

Freeze the first three columns (Survey, Workstream, Action Item) so they stay visible when scrolling right.

Step 8 — Column widths

Set column widths: Action Item = 38, Owner = 22, Status = 14, Workstream = 22, Priority = 11, Start and End = 13. Auto-fit row heights.


Honest heads-up about Excel Copilot:
Copilot handles steps 1–5 and 7–8 well. Step 6 (the Gantt bars) is the hardest for it — if it struggles, use this manual fallback:

Select your first Gantt column's data cells (e.g. I4:I50)
Home → Conditional Formatting → New Rule → "Use a formula"
Enter: =AND($G4<=I$3+4, $H4>=I$3)
Set blue fill, then copy the rule across all Gantt columns

That one step is genuinely easier done manually than through Copilot.
